<table border="0" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#000000" width="100%"><tr><td align="left">
<span class="title">Jeff Hickman Customer Service Report</span><BR>
<font size="2">Posted on Saturday, November 03 @ 11:20:14 EST by <a href="http://www.kyid.net/daoc/">Taoism</a></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="2%"><img src="themes/nukesolution/images/left_title.jpg" width="30" height="7"></td><td width="95%" background="themes/nukesolution/images/line_title.jpg"><img src="themes/nukesolution/images/pixel.gif" width="1" height="1"></td><td width="3%"><img src="themes/nukesolution/images/right_title.jpg" width="31" height="7"></td></tr></table></td></tr></table>
<a href="search.php?query=&amp;topic=34"><img src="images/topics/daoc.jpg" border="0" Alt="DAoC General" align="right" hspace="10" vspace="10"></a>
<font size="2" color="#505050">Jeff Hickman posted <a href="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?topic=18801157">this</a> customer service report to the Vault Network message boards yesterday morning.
<br><br>
I thought I would post it here since I know alot of people are wondering about the in game customer service these days.
<br><br><br><br> Article below.<br><br>
===============================
<br><br>
I was going to write an update for CS for all of you to view this week, but decided that instead of writing something abridged for you all, I would post the full text of my Weekly Executive report.  This is the same information that Mythic's President and Vice President receive weekly.
 <br> 
 <br> =======================
 <br> Weekly Executive report for DAoC Customer Support.  10/25/01 - 11/1/01.
 <br> 
 <br> Overview: 
 <br> 	Things are generally improving within the support department, though we are still FAR from the levels of service that we want and need to provide.  We have streamlined many of our processes and implemented many of the programmatical and procedural changes that we have been planning for the last several months.  Our processes are doing very well in handling the types of issues that are being brought to our attention, though we are still buried under the sheer volume of issues that continue to arise.  Here is the Good and the Not So Good:
 <br> 
 <br> The Good:  
 <br> 1.  Our overall ticket count has dropped significantly since last week.  We have dropped from over 13,000 active tickets to under 7,000 tickets right now.  This is mostly due to the changes that we made in our processes and in our appeal system.  The added ability for our customers to cancel their own appeals has been a tremendous improvement.
 <br> 2.  Our average response time last week at this time was over 7 days (this is ticket age, not actual time the customer waited online).  This is an average - Some people waited much longer, while others waited a much shorter period, depending on severity of the issue.  Average response time is now just over 4 days.
 <br> 3.  Stuck issues have dropped significantly.  We had around 2800 stuck issues during the week last week, and have only had around 1700 this week.  This number will continue to improve with more improvements to /Stuck, especially in the cities.
 <br> 4.  We are routing Harassment, Conduct Reports, and Stuck issues much more efficiently now.  This enables us to jump on these critical issues quickly, and get them resolved as efficiently as possible.
 <br> 5.  Our technical support (telephone and e-mail), is doing very well.  They have resolved over 16,000 issues since release, with an average hold time of under 4 minutes, and an average turn around time on e-mail of under 24 hours.
 <br> 
 <br> The Not So Good:
 <br> 1.  We are still far behind on many tickets.  This will continue to improve, but it is going to take some time to get anywhere close to where we need to be.
 <br> 2.  We still need to refine some of our tools that will help us with name changes.  We are getting more and more naming issues reported to us, mostly from the roleplaying servers.  This should be our next big push.
 <br>  
 <br> The Numbers - 10/25/01 - 11/1/01:
 <br> 
 <br> Total Tickets resolved:  15207
 <br> Total Tickets cancelled by customers:  8765
 <br> Total Active Tickets in the queue (Noon, 11/02/01):  6482
 <br> Average Response time:  4 Days, 7 hours.
 <br> Average Resolution time:  4 minutes, 58 seconds.
 <br> Top 4 issues (resolved):  
 <br> -Bug Issues:  2447
 <br> -Stuck Issues:  1704      
 <br> -Quest Issues:  975
 <br> -Violation Issues:  643         
 <br> 
 <br> 
 <br> Hot Spots:
 <br> 1.  We are starting to see a jump in societal appeals from RvR combat.  I predict that these will continue to jump dramatically over the next couple of weeks.  We will be monitoring this very closely for problem areas.
 <br> 2.  Speed Hackers:  We saw a decline in our blatant hacker population after last weeks' bannings.  We continue to detect, track and observe 2 - 3 new hackers a day.  Once it is proven that they are indeed cheating, we immediately terminate their accounts.  We will continue to monitor this and take action as necessary.
 <br> 3.  Bug Issues and Quest Bugs are a rising concern also.  We are re-evaluating our procedures to make sure that we are closing the loop with our customers properly, when dealing with these types of issues.
 <br> 
 <br> Plans for Next Week:
 <br> 	We will continue to analyze and improve any of our processes that have weaknesses.  I am constantly monitoring the /Stuck issues, Harassment issues, and the overall ticket counts per hour.  I will have an analysis of future programming and staffing needs within the next week.  
 <br> 
 <br> 
 <br> I am going to post this on the Vault also.
 <br> Let me know if you have any questions or concerns.
 <br> 
 <br> -Jeff
 <br> 		
</font>
</td></tr></table><br>


